In JavaScript, you can express the union of two sets using the Set data structure and the spread operator. Here's an example:

```javascript
let setS = new Set(["white toddler girls"]);
let setT = new Set(["African American males"]);

let unionSet = new Set([...setS, ...setT]);

console.log(unionSet);
```

This code creates two sets, `setS` and `setT`, containing the respective elements. The spread operator `...` is used to combine the elements of both sets into a new set called `unionSet`. Finally, `unionSet` will contain all the elements from `setS` and `setT`. The resulting set can be displayed in the console using `console.log(unionSet)`.

Certainly! Here are simplified variants for expressing a set union in different programming languages:

Python:
```python
set_s = {"white toddler girls"}
set_t = {"African American males"}

union_set = set_s.union(set_t)

print(union_set)
```

Java:
```java
import java.util.HashSet;
import java.util.Set;

public class SetUnionExample {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Set<String> setS = new HashSet<>();
        Set<String> setT = new HashSet<>();

        setS.add("white toddler girls");
        setT.add("African American males");

        Set<String> unionSet = new HashSet<>(setS);
        unionSet.addAll(setT);

        System.out.println(unionSet);
    }
}
```

C#:
```csharp
using System;
using System.Collections.Generic;

public class SetUnionExample {
    public static void Main(string[] args) {
        HashSet<string> setS = new HashSet<string>() { "white toddler girls" };
        HashSet<string> setT = new HashSet<string>() { "African American males" };

        HashSet<string> unionSet = new HashSet<string>(setS);
        unionSet.UnionWith(setT);

        Console.WriteLine(string.Join(", ", unionSet));
    }
}
```

These examples demonstrate how to create sets or hashsets in the respective languages and perform a union operation to merge the elements from different sets into a new set. The resulting union set is then printed or displayed.
